vectorData.altText: 19. The ______________ _______________ is the combined testicular vessels, nerves, lymphatics and the vas deferens.
That's right! Testis is connected to the body through the spermatic cord, a structure consists of the testicular vessels, nerves, lymphatics and vas deferens.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

As the fetus develops and enlarges, the positions of the gonads change, such that the ovaries come to rest in the pelvic cavity and the testicles, by birth, occupy the scrotum.  In the male, this developmental process is called, “the descent of the testes”. 
Gonadal blood vessels, lymphatics and nerves lengthen as the gonads migrate during development to their final position. 
The path taken by the testicles to the scrotum is determined by the gubernaculum, and as such, the testicles pass alongside the processus vaginalis, between it and the layers of the abdominal wall that cover it.
Each testis remains connected to the body by its spermatic cord, which consists of testicular vessels, nerves and lymphatics, as well as its efferent duct, the vas deferens.
The testes and spermatic cord, as they pass alongside the processus vaginalis, take a covering from the each of the layers of the abdominal wall.
When the descent of the testes is complete, a remnant of the gubernaculum is found in the scrotum attaching the inferior pole of the testis to the scrotum.
